023-01-27T07:46:23Z", "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "<!--\r\nThank you for filing a bug report! \ud83d\udc1b Please provide a short summary of the bug,\r\nalong with any information you feel relevant to replicating the bug.\r\n-->\r\n\r\nI tried this code:\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nenum MyEnum {\r\n  NotMyEnum,\r\n  Is(MyEnum)\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nI expected to see this happen: since there is indirection in this enum (`NotMyEnum`), it should compile perfectly fine since this can be represented normally.\r\n\r\nInstead, this happened: `rustc` complained that the type *must* be of infinite size, despite there being a source of indirection.\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nerror[E0072]: recursive type `MyEnum` has infinite size\r\n  --> src\\parser.rs:42:1\r\n   |\r\n42 | enum MyEnum {\r\n   | ^^^^^^^^^^^ recursive type has infinite size\r\n43 |     NotMyEnum,\r\n44 |     Is(MyEnum)\r\n   |        ------ recursive without indirection\r\n   |\r\nhelp: insert some indirection (e.g., a `Box`, `Rc`, or `&`) to make `MyEnum` representable\r\n   |\r\n44 |     Is(Box<MyEnum>)\r\n   |        ++++      +\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Meta\r\n<!--\r\nIf you're using the stable version of the compiler, you should also check if the\r\nbug also exists in the beta or nightly versions.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n`rustc --version --verbose`:\r\n```\r\nrustc 1.57.0-nightly (54bb4fec6 2021-10-08)\r\nbinary: rustc\r\ncommit-hash: 54bb4fec68cb592e23077896baea072919721573\r\ncommit-date: 2021-10-08\r\nhost: x86_64-pc-windows-msvc\r\nrelease: 1.57.0-nightly\r\nLLVM version: 13.0.0\r\n```\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nInclude a backtrace in the code block by setting `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` in your\r\nenvironment. E.g. `RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo build`.\r\n-->\r\n<details><summary>Backtrace</summary>\r\n<p>\r\n\r\nThe output with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` does not differ from regular output (tested on Apple M1, on stable).\r\n</p>\r\n</details>\r\n", "closed_by": {"login": "workingjubilee", "id": 46493976, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcj